network protocols:

 

              TCP:

                             connection oriented:

                                           handshake process

                                                          send, reply, send, connection established

                             acknowledgements

                                           allows to know if you need to retransmit packets

                             sequence numbers

                                           allows you to guarantee order of data, avoid corruption

                             checksums

                             congestion/flow control

                                           both for senders and reciever

                             prioritizes reliability over all else

              UDP:

                             popular for video for eg.

                             no verification of readiness or acknowledgements

                             order is not guaranteed

                             no congestion or flow control

                             still has checksums though

                             can multicast (broadcasting to all intended recipients only)

                             simpler and faster to implement than TCP

              HTTP:

                             also response/request protocols

                             older version use TCP as underlying

                             newer versions use QUIC:

                                           reduced latencies, built on top of UDP

                             all connections considered persistent unless proven otherwise

                             does multiplexing

                                           multiple requests sent over tcp without waiting for response

                            

              blocking vs non-blocking IO:

